stories.text:
Hey HackerNews --

Imagine being able to meet up with others in the area in tech. We’re aiming to put together a tech happy hour.

We think this would be a great way to meet other engineers. I’m an engineer at Netflix. YC founders, bankers, and engineering friends are in too.

We’d like to see if we can do this once a month.

What do we think about this?

Details: Calendar Link: https://www.eventbrite.com/e/sf-tech-happy-hour-tickets-170239096721 LOCATION: Spark Social in Mission Bay, San Francisco TIME: After work (6PM) - Thursday, 9/24
stories.title: SF Tech Happy Hour on the 30th

stories.text:
I recently setup my own CalDAV and CardDAV server (using Radicale https://radicale.org/3.0.html), and I wondered how I can send and receive objects from this server (implementation). This journey let me read the CardDAV RFC (https://tools.ietf.org/rfcmarkup?doc=6352).

Now I want to practice implementing RFCs, since I hav e never done that before. It looks like the CardDAV one is quite big (?) for the first try.

So I wondered: Do you recommend or know a RFC which is easy/small to implement so I can get my feet wet?
stories.title: Ask HN: What is a small(ish) RFC to implement for learning purposes?

stories.text: The password import (from CSV) option used to be available as an experimental feature via chrome://flags. It's completely disappeared. Can't be enabled via command line arguments. Was at one point implemented in Edge, but is missing from there too, so maybe was killed upstream in Chromium? Not finding any info about it...
